Cabinet Painting in Stayton, OR – Sprayed, Cured & Glass-Like Finish 🎨✨

We’re working on a cabinet painting project in Stayton, Oregon, giving these cabinets a high-end new look with Miller Paint’s Picholine—a rich, earthy green that’s going to pair beautifully with gold hardware.

This isn’t brush and roller work—we sprayed these cabinets in our professional spray booth using Sherwin-Williams Gallery Series for that true, factory-quality finish.

Here’s the setup:
• Graco GX-19 sprayer
• 308 FFLP tip
• Spraying at 1,000–1,300 PSI, using a crosshatch technique for a consistent 3–4 wet mils
• Cured in our climate-controlled drying room at 77–90°F with humidity kept below 50% for a strong, durable finish

✅ Flawless, smooth, glass-like results
✅ Designed for long-term durability
✅ And best of all—painting your cabinets is a fraction of the cost of replacing them

Why Two Coats Matter 🎯 | Exterior Painting – West Salem, OR

In today’s video, I’m spraying the exterior of this home using Sherwin-Williams SuperPaint Satin and my go-to Hyde Extension Wand. This tool helps me maintain consistent distance and overlap, especially on taller walls—resulting in a smoother, more even finish.

But let’s talk about the real game-changer: two coats.
One coat just doesn’t cut it—uneven coverage, flashing, and long-term durability issues are all too common. That second coat ensures a uniform, rich finish that’s built to last through Oregon’s elements.

🎨 Product: Sherwin-Williams SuperPaint Exterior Satin
🛠️ Gear: Titan 640 Sprayer + Hyde Extension Wand + 515 Tip
